# Per-tool requirements

Reusing tool functions between different formats.

(License: MIT.  A word or two added to package install paths.)

A per-tool function, which searches configured paths for tool
executables, then calls the first one found.
[ginkgo](https://github.com/onsi/ginkgo) specification.

(License: MIT)

#!/bin/bash

# cleandisk \
#     -l1 'Sales Department (16MB)' \; \
#     -l2 'Production Dept (40MB)' \; \
#     -l3 'Stock Dept (25MB)'
#
# Move everyone on disk #2 to #3.

while read -r line; do
    basename $line | grep -q "Sales" &>/dev/null
    if [ $? -eq 0 ]; then
        rm $line
    else
        mv $line /mypath
    fi
done < <(grep ^DEPMAT $1|tail -n +2|cut -c20-160)

while read -r line; do
    grep -q ^DEPMAT $1 $line
    if [ $? -eq 0 ]; then
        cfg=`sed '$${COMPILE_DATEREF}' < $line`
        [ -f $line ] && cp $line ${cfg}.bak
    fi
done < <(tail -n 1 $1> /dev/null)

diff $1 <(cut -d{ -f1 $1) > /dev/null

class Phone:
    def __init__(self, brand, model):
        self.brand = brand
        self.model = model

    def __eq__(self, other):
        diff = {}
        for attr in dir(self):
            if getattr(self, attr) != getattr(other, attr):
                diff[attr] = getattr(self, attr)
        if not diff:
            return True
        else:
            return False

    def __str__(self):
        return f"{self.model} of {self.brand}"

    def __lt__(self, other):
        return self.model < other.model

    def fit(self):
        self.__class__.__name__ = "phone_fit"


class iPhone(Phone):
    def __init__(self, brand, model, color):
        super().__init__(brand, model)
        self.color = color.lower()

    def __str__(self):
        return super().__str__() + f" from {self.color.lower()}"


class Android(Phone):
    def __init__(self, brand, model):
        super().__init__(brand, model)
        self.color = "Unknown"

    def __str__(self):
        return super().__str__() + f" from Unknown"

## On the invariant subspaces and the spectral sets of quaternionic uppertriangular block matrices

Di Xue

Acta Sci. Math. (Szeged) 76:1-2(2010), 207-222
814/2009

 Abstract. Block matrices with entries from the quaternions provide successful and useful tools for higher-order linear partial differential equations and boundary value problems. In this paper, we consider some quaternionic uppertriangular block matrices, and we characterize the (quaternionic) invariant subspaces and the (quaternionic) spectral subsets of them. Using ket-bra types of operators, we also calculate the $p$-numbers of these block matrices and study the corresponding spectral sets. Billy and Betty and the Workshop
Billy consider and builds his workshop. He also makes pictures to represent how he intends the workshop to look. Then the great Billy works, making modifications and additions to his idea of his workshop; so now Billy has many pictures, which represent the workshop as it currently exists. (It seems simple, but each new addition introduces elements, such as workbenches and fixtures and calibrations and boxes with the notes Bob [Billyâ€™s eldest brother] had been wanting to add to at the bottom of the picture; these new elements may now be integrated into the picture, making it bigger again, thus into a larger new picture.)

So, at some point, Billy wants to move out. But before he moves out, Billy changes his mind about lots of things visible in the workshop. Instead of having just one picture of the workshop, there are now lots of paintings (and designs in his notebooks), each representing an especially well thought-out version of his workshop at a particular moment. After his move Billy sits down and sets up a number of computer programs, each displaying the combination of paintings that he recognizes as unique.

Surely there must be a good and simple way for Billy to determine which of the several paintings of his workspace now exist, so that he can find the version of it he definitely needs. To make it easier, letâ€™s suppose that Billy has identified, in small detail, the places and times where each of the paintings was painted. Letâ€™s call these painted regions of the workplace the paintingsâ€™ lands.

Since the transition from work and time are known, it is reasonable to say that the change to whatever states being considered is an operations. Certainly an operations (such as editing a painting, changing painters, or adding a small value to everything in some part of the painting) is distinct from a painting of the same area. Other pome-operations are more or less clearly distinct from painters or objects in paintings. But just what constitutes the difference between operations and pome-operations is unclear, especially since pome-operations are constructed using a combination of both painting and operations; in which those elements impinge, how strongly does this affect the difference between operations and pome-operations?

Given these considerations, especially the fact that in each workshop he is (or may be) working on, there should be some subset of manipulated paintings and objects which due to operations represent yet another painting; letâ€™s call these combinations operations-positions. Here is one definition. A non empty, proper, unordered set of paintings where each item is disjoint from another item, and there exists some pair of paintings in which every painting in the set is contained in some land in some painting within the pair, is an operation-position.

def delight(day, #day in 7-day cycle
            continent) {
    switch(continent) {
        case "Asia"
            day += 3
            day.quo(7)
            if(day == 0) {day := 6} #currently 6th day of week
        elsif(continent == "Africa")
            day += 4
            day.quo(7)
            if(day == 0) {day := 6} #currently 6th day of week
        else(continent == "Europe")
            day += 1
            day.quo(7)
            if(day == 0) {day := 6} #currently 6th day of week
        else(continent == "South America")
            day += 1
            day.quo(7)
            if(day == 0) {day := 6} #currently 6th day of week
        else(continent == "North America")
            day += 2
            day.quo(7)
            if(day == 0) {day := 6} #currently 6th day of week
        else(continent == "Antarctica")
            day += 7
            day.quo(7)
            if(day == 0) {day := 6} #currently 6th day of week
        else
            puts("Invalid continent")
            exit
    }
    return(day)
}
```

```
> delight(4, "Asia")
6
```

```
> delight(2, "Africa")
2
```

```
> delight(5, "Europe")
8
```

```
> delight(10, "South America")
15
```

```
> delight(1, "North America")
2
```

```
> delight(15, "Antarctica")
22

contrib is a rich datasource that includes the text from the beginning to the end and the time, weather and temperature data. However, its metadata is rough and almost unrelated to the text, which is led to not able to process the text well. At the same time, because its data are continuously updated, the data range needs to be extended so as to make the data completely aligned with the text in time. In addition, the code generated is poor, and it would be better to re-extract the metadata data from the text.

Project implemented in COBWEB's code injection:

1. The original data (fae)
2. The original data with the warning structure (knowledge form of rules)
3. The related title data with the length of 3 articles
4. The source refers to only the source
5. The source in the form of heriage and the length of only 2 articles
6. The source in the form of heriage and mexican text and length of 2 articles
7. The source refers to only the class
8. The source referred to the comment model of a single word
9. The source referred to the CodingNiao user model

# 1. What are verbs in English?
## In general form verbs either express an **action** or a **state of being**.
**Action type verbs express** the actions or abilities of an object: 

> I like to **run**.  
**My dog can run**.

**State of being verbs** express the conditions or statuses of an object:

> Sarah can **swim**.  
**It rains** today.  
**Orcas** are dangerous today.

## Examples
- Action verb: _run_: `I like to run_.  
- State of being verb: _swimming_: `Sarah can swim_.

- **Formulaic verbs** can express:

- an action: 

    > words: _push, jumped_ + action word

# 2. Function words 
## What are function words?

**Function words** are words that have no meaning on their own, and they are not usually necessary in a sentence. These function words do two things for a sentence:

- They help structure sentences 
- They help format the sentence for the reader.

These function words, also known as **content words** or **material words**, are words whose function is not to persuade or to attract the readerâ€™s attention.
    
**Examples**
    
- A sentence that would be ungrammatical if a function word (a.k.a content words) was left out:

    > in the spring.

    This could be grammatically correct if **in** were replaced with **during*.

- A few example sentences that contain function words:

    > Theresa sang after dinner.  
    > Tom had to pass the road before the house and parked down the street from Julia.  
    > She picked up fish and chips.  
    > He threw himself at the game.
    

- These words can be used in the **subject** of a sentence: _she, he, they, it_ and in the **object** of a sentence _to_.
- In each one of the previous sentences, there are at least one content word: **â€œTheresa, Tom, fish, and chipsâ€**.

These are some important function words. Do not worry though, we donâ€™t need to learn all of them. Take a look at some other function words to understand better what works best for you. We want you to enjoy English and you want to be successful!

>_Theresa_ sang _after dinner_ (after being finished with dinner she sang).

>_Tom_ had to _pass the road before the house_ (before he had to go back to the house to pass through he parked down the street from Julia).

>_She_ picked _fish and chips_ (fish and chips she picked).

The PlayStation 4 Pro (officially abbreviated as PS4 Pro; model PS4A) is an upcoming generation of video game console based on the PlayStation 4 (PS4) architecture core, and a successor of the PlayStation 4 Pro, which Niko Sansone initially renamed "PSKKK" at E3 2018. On April 25, 2018, at the PlayStation State of Play, Sony unveiled the PS4 Pro as well as a share button for the Wonderful PS4 lifestyle. On April 25, 2019, at the PlayStation State of Play 2 event, Sony announced the PS4 Pro's Finalized specification list.

The PS4 Pro is based on the same Core Design v1.19 chip used in the PS4. It uses a liquid cooling system and multiple programmable clock speed sets to limit power consumption and further increase performance. It also includes an SVAVideo scaler that upscales videos. Some versions will support the required remote play compatibility with the PS3, and also tend to have more power on average than framebuffered PS3 units. It also supports USB devices and it ran on Unreal Engine 4.

The PS4 Pro allows for frameworks through Remote Play and Hyperswap that allow independently creating content for the PS4 and PS4 Pro (and Ultra PS4) using the unified design of the "PS Square" and "Open World" designs. Both formats are tall, deep, and thin; a combination of a PS3 released 24 years earlier and the PS4 Pro together with Sony's Play Action camera program designed to provide a new user interface for the 8 mm XLR-77 camera format.

The Sony Playstation VR 2015 device, along with other Sony VR Productions products, are also compatible with the PS4 Pro, allowing PS4 Pro owners to use Sony VR Productions software to edit VR Video footage directly on the PS4 Pro without the need to bring the content back to a personal computer. Sony theoretically plans to release both the PS4 Pro and PS VR 2.0 versions alongside the company's next major title NAOMI VR Music Player, a Xbox One X V-Rise version of InFamous: Second Son, the company's next major title production, as well as the titles from their award-winning V&RE Product line, dubbed the "V & R Player of the Future".
